
Legendary Difficulty — BASELINE RULES (no longer an optional module)

This document's rules ARE the standard rules of this campaign ("Toryggs legacy uses this"). As of the July 2026 rules consolidation:
- The Critical rule (x2 on a Natural 1), Villain Actions, and Phase Bars are all stated in the baseline docs (Reference tables / players guide) — the versions here are the same rules, kept for the worked examples.
- THE HP MULTIPLIERS IN SECTION 3 ARE ALREADY BAKED INTO the Scaled Monster Statistics table in GM Guide/Reference tables. NEVER apply them a second time on top of that table. Section 3 remains only as the record of how those HP values were derived.
- The FORMULA OF PAIN below is the system-wide authority on damage stacking: add all flats first, then MULTIPLY all multipliers together (they never add). The worked examples in this file are the canonical reference whenever stacking is in doubt.
- The "x2 Damage" items in the examples (Titan Gloves) are unique GM-granted artifacts, not commissionable enchantments.

1. The Core Rule: Lethal Criticals

In this mode, a Critical Success is not merely a hit with a bonus; it is a devastation.

The Rule: On a Natural 1, calculate your total damage (Weapon + Perks + FP spend + Magic), then multiply the final result by 2.

2. The Formula of Pain: Calculating Damage

To keep combat fast and intuitive, damage is calculated in a specific order of operations.

Step 1: The Base Hit
Add up all flat numbers first.
(Weapon Damage + Perks + Power Attack Cost + Magic Buffs) = Base Hit

Step 2: The Multipliers
Multiply your Base Hit by any active multipliers. If you have more than one (e.g., a Magic Item that doubles damage and a Critical Hit), multiply them together.

Base Hit x [Item Multiplier] x [Crit Multiplier] = Total Damage

Example: The "Nova Strike"

Base Hit: 14 (Claws) + 2 (Fire) = 16

Magic Item: x2 Damage

Critical Hit: x2 Damage

Calculation: 16 x 2 x 2 = 64 Total Damage.

Scenario A: The Assassin's Burst (Sneak Attack + Crit)

Use Case: Understanding how Sneak Attack multipliers interact with Critical Hits on a standard physical attack.

The Setup:
Silas the Rogue fires a Daedric Bow from the shadows. He has the Assassin's Blade perk (x3 Sneak Damage) and he rolls a Natural 1 (Critical Hit).

Step 1: The Base Hit

Daedric Bow: 9 Damage

Ebony Arrow: +2 Damage

Base Hit Total: 11 Physical Damage

Step 2: The Multipliers

Sneak Attack Perk: x3 Multiplier

Critical Hit: x2 Multiplier

Calculation: 11 (Base) x 3 (Sneak) x 2 (Crit) = 66 Damage

Step 3: The Result

The target is a Draugr Deathlord (DR 6).

66 - 6 = 60 HP Lost.

Scenario B: The Spellblade (Mixed Damage + Weakness)

Use Case: Calculating damage when an enemy is weak to only ONE part of your attack (e.g., Fire), but not the physical weapon itself.

The Setup:
Valerius swings a Sword of Burning at a Frost Troll (Weak to Fire x2). He does not Crit.

Step 1: Separate the Damage Types
You must calculate the Physical damage and Elemental damage separately first.

Physical: 6 (Sword) + 1 (Power Attack) = 7 Physical

Fire: 3 (Enchantment) + 2 (Arcane Edge) = 5 Fire

Step 2: Apply Weakness Multiplier
The Frost Troll is vulnerable to Fire, not Steel. Multiply only the Fire portion.

Physical: 7 (No Multiplier) = 7

Fire: 5 x 2 (Vulnerability) = 10

New Total Base: 7 + 10 = 17 Mixed Damage

Step 3: Apply Global Multipliers

No Crits or other multipliers active.

Final Damage: 17.

Step 4: The Result

The Troll has Thick Hide (DR 4).

17 - 4 = 13 HP Lost.

Scenario C: The Nova (Crit + Weakness + Magic Item)

Use Case: The "Kyboh Situation." High stacking modifiers with Elemental Weakness involved.

The Setup:
Kyboh punches a Dryad (Weak to Fire x2). He uses Arcane Edge (Fire). He has his Titan Gloves (x2 Damage) active. He rolls a Critical Hit (x2 Damage).

Step 1: Separate the Damage Types

Physical: 14 (Claws)

Fire: 2 (Arcane Edge)

Step 2: Apply Weakness Multiplier First
Resolve the specific enemy weakness before applying your own buffs.

Physical: 14 (Unchanged)

Fire: 2 x 2 (Weakness) = 4

Adjusted Base Hit: 14 + 4 = 18 Base Damage

Step 3: Apply Global Multipliers
Now apply your Gloves and Crit to the Adjusted Base.

Multipliers: x2 (Gloves) and x2 (Crit).

Calculation: 18 (Adjusted Base) x 2 x 2 = 72 Total Damage.

Step 4: The Result

The Dryad has Barkskin (DR 3).

72 - 3 = 69 HP Lost.

Scenario D: The Twin-Blade (Multi-Hit Attacks)

Use Case: Handling abilities that grant extra attacks (like Dual Flurry). Multipliers usually only apply to the specific hit that triggered them.

The Setup:
Bjorn uses Dual Flurry to attack twice in one turn against a Bandit.

Hit 1: A standard hit.

Hit 2: A Critical Hit (Nat 1).

Attack 1 Calculation:

Base: 6 (Sword) + 1 (Perk) = 7.

Multipliers: None.

Result: 7 - 4 (Enemy DR) = 3 Damage.

Attack 2 Calculation:

Base: 6 (Sword) + 1 (Perk) = 7.

Multipliers: x2 (Critical Hit).

Total: 14.

Result: 14 - 4 (Enemy DR) = 10 Damage.

Total Turn Damage: 3 + 10 = 13 HP Lost.
(Note: DR is subtracted from each hit individually, not from the total sum.)

Step 3: The Result
Tell the GM the Total Damage. The GM will subtract the enemy's Damage Reduction (DR) to find the final HP lost.

3. Legendary Scaling: Cinematic Durability

Because player damage output is massive in this mode, enemy resilience must scale to match. Enemies are no longer simulations of biology; they are cinematic obstacles designed to withstand heroic punishment.

The HP Multiplier
When generating enemies using the standard Threat Level table, apply the following modifiers to their Health Points (HP) only. Do not multiply their Damage or DR.

Minions (TL 1): Base HP x 2

Lieutenants (TL 2): Base HP x 2.5

Bosses (TL 3): Base HP x 3

Designer's Note: Do not increase the enemy's Damage Reduction (DR). High DR frustrates players by nullifying their attacks. High HP allows them to see high damage numbers while ensuring the enemy survives long enough to be a threat.

4. Boss Mechanics: The Phase System

In Legendary Difficulty, high HP is not enough. A lucky round of Criticals from five players can still delete a 500 HP dragon instantly. To ensure Boss battles feel epic, use HP Gates.

The Rule of Phases
Bosses do not have a single Health Bar. They have 2 or 3 distinct Phase Bars.

Damage Stop: Damage never carries over between phases.

The Transition: When a Phase Bar reaches 0, any remaining damage from that specific hit is discarded. The boss clears all status effects, triggers a dramatic change (sheds armor, flies into the air, enters a rage), and the next Phase Bar begins at full health.

Example in Play:
A Dragon has 450 HP, split into three Phases of 150 HP each.
A warrior lands a massive "Nova Strike" for 64 damage when the Dragon has only 10 HP left in Phase 1.

Result: The dragon takes 10 damage. Phase 1 ends. The remaining 54 damage is discarded. The Dragon roars, changing tactics, and Phase 2 begins with 150 HP.

5. Action Economy: Villain Actions

A party of 5 heroes has 5 Major Actions per round. A single Boss has 1. In high-power games, the Boss will be crowd-controlled and beaten down before they can act.

The Fix: Bosses take Villain Actions outside of their normal turn.

Trigger: At the end of every second player's turn, the Boss may take one Villain Action.

Villain Actions: These are distinct from their Major Attacks. They are crowd control or movement abilities designed to shake up the battlefield (e.g., Wing Buffet, Terrifying Roar, Tactical Retreat, Summon Minion).


